This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Plea/sentencing hearing on November 17, 2022 at 10:00 am.

2:46 PM Defendant Ashley J Dowling in court.  Attorney Amanda Marie Nimmer in court for Ashley J Dowling. District Attorney's Office Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin by Julian Marrufo. Victim rights have been complied with by the Waukesha County District Attorneys Office. 

Defense states that the Defendant paid $2025 of restitution to the State. $3045 is the total up front restitution amount. However, Defense has not heard back from the State as to if they agree to the restitution that was already paid. Defense requests another plea/sentencing hearing. 
State does not have any notes regarding restitution that was paid. 
Court sets.
